"Naik H., Naqvi S.W.A., Suresh T., Narvekar P.V.","Impact of a tropical cyclone on biogeochemistry of the central Arabian Sea",2008,"Global Biogeochemical Cycles","22","3", GB3020,"","",,,10.1029/2007GB003028,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-65549140093&partnerID=40&md5=cffa4cfc540eee440a5bff93d4b5d413","National Institute of Oceanography, Dona Paula, Goa, India; National Institute of Oceanography, Dona Paula, Goa 403 004, India","Naik, H., National Institute of Oceanography, Dona Paula, Goa, India, National Institute of Oceanography, Dona Paula, Goa 403 004, India; Naqvi, S.W.A., National Institute of Oceanography, Dona Paula, Goa, India, National Institute of Oceanography, Dona Paula, Goa 403 004, India; Suresh, T., National Institute of Oceanography, Dona Paula, Goa, India, National Institute of Oceanography, Dona Paula, Goa 403 004, India; Narvekar, P.V., National Institute of Oceanography, Dona Paula, Goa, India, National Institute of Oceanography, Dona Paula, Goa 403 004, India","Remotely sensed data are combined with shipboard measurements to investigate biogeochemical changes caused by a moderate tropical cyclone in the central Arabian Sea in December 1998. The sea surface temperature decreased by ∼4°C, whereas surface nitrate and chlorophyll concentrations increased by &gt;5 M and up to 4 mg m-3, respectively, over a large area affected by the cyclone. Nutrient enrichment in the surface layer of the cyclone-affected zone is estimated to have supported a new production of ∼4.2 Tg C, approximately 5% of the annual organic carbon export to the deep sea (beyond the continental margin) for the entire Arabian Sea. Entrainment of nitrous oxide from the thermocline led to more than doubling of its concentration in the mixed layer. The cyclone also resulted in an increase in nitrous oxide inventory within the oxygen minimum zone. Our results imply that, should there be an increase in the frequency and intensity of tropical cyclones as a result of global warming, as projected in some recent reports, carbon production and respiration, and redox processes within the oxygen minimum zones, such as the production of nitrous oxide through nitrification/ denitrification, and of molecular nitrogen through denitrification/anaerobic ammonium oxidation, may be significantly impacted. Copyright 2008 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Ammonium oxidations; Arabian seas; Carbon productions; Chlorophyll concentrations; Continental margins; Deep seas; Mixed layers; Molecular nitrogens; New productions; Nitrous oxides; Nutrient enrichments; Oxygen minimum zones; Redox process; Remotely sensed datum; Sea surface temperatures; Shipboard measurements; Surface layers; Surface nitrates; Tropical cyclones; Ammonium compounds; Atmospheric temperature; Biogeochemistry; Chlorophyll; Fire hazards; Global warming; Molecular oxygen; Nitrogen oxides; Organic carbon; Porphyrins; Seawater; Storms; Tropics; Anesthetics; ammonium; biogeochemistry; chlorophyll; denitrification; global warming; nitrate; nitrous oxide; nutrient enrichment; organic carbon; oxidation; oxygen minimum layer; remote sensing; satellite data; sea surface temperature; thermocline; tropical cyclone; Arabian Sea; Indian Ocean",,,,,,"Babin, S.M., Carton, J.A., Dickey, T.D., Wiggert, J.D., Satellite evidence of hurricane-induced phytoplankton blooms in an oceanic desert (2004) J. Geophys. Res., 109, pp. C03043. , doi:10.1029/2003JC001938; Bange, H.W., Rapsomanikis, S., Andreae, M.O., Nitrous oxide cycling in the Arabian Sea (2001) J. Geophys. Res., 106 (C1), pp. 1053-1065. , doi:10.1029/1999JC000284; Bange, H.W., Naqvi, S.W.A., Codispoti, L.A., The nitrogen cycle in the Arabian Sea (2005) Prog. Oceanogr., 65, pp. 145-158. , doi:10.1016/ j.pocean.2005.03.002; Banse, K., Overview of the hydrography and associated biological phenomena in the Arabian off Pakistan (1984) Marine Geology and Oceano- Graphy of Arabian Sea and Coastal Pakistan, pp. 271-303. , edited by B. U. Haq a